3 Marginal scans

We compare two scans:

  1. centers: we included the only random effect (1|ccenter)
  2. centers + arm: we included two random effects (1|ccenter) and (1|sid)
    • (1|sid) has the var-covar matrix equal to ARM (not GARM).

Onservations

  • The first scan centers produces inflated test statistics.
    • the inflation is less for traits with the lower h2_arm
      • FVCpp_utah (h2_arm 0.006, lambda 1.03)
      • FVC_utah (h2_arm 0.007, lambda 1.06)
  • The second scan centers + arm is able to produce good qq-plots (the inflation factor is between 0.94 and 1.03).

4 Interaction scans

We compare two scans:

  1. centers: we included the only random effect (1|ccenter)
  2. centers + arm + arm_d: we included three random effects (1|ccenter), (1|sid) and (1|esid)
    • (1|sid) has the var-covar matrix equal to ARM (not GARM).
    • (1|esid) (e stands for environment) has the var-covar matrix equal to ARM * D (element-wise multiplication)
    • D is a relationship matrix due to exposure (SmokCigNow)

Onservations

  • The second scan centers + arm + arm_d does improves the inflation in comparison to the first scan centers, but the inflation is still high.
    • A possible explanation is inaccurate or even completely erroneous estimation of variance components
  • The only acceptable inflation for the second scan centers + arm + arm_d is shown for low-heritability traits
    • FVCpp_utah (h2_arm 0, h2_arm_d 0.04, lambda 1.06)
    • FVC_utah (h2_arm 0, h2_arm_d 0.03, lambda 1.06)

5 Conclusion

Possible explanations of inflated statistics in the interaction analysis (LMM + GLS):

  • estimated variance components are far from the true ones
  • imbalance in exposed and unexposed groups

Things to do:

  • run the interaction analysis (LMM + GLS) in a different way
    • centers + arm instead of centers + arm + arm_d
  • run simulations with known variance components
  • run simulations with balanced exposed and unexposed groups
